<HEAD>Aaron Elkins Wins Edgar</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will stand for PMs.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Old Bones,'' a mystery novel set in France and
reaching back to World War II, won the Edgar from the Mystery
Writers of America for its writer Aaron Elkins.
   Edgars, named for Edgar Allan Poe, were presented for best
mystery works of 1987 at a banquet Thursday night during the
convention of the International Congress of Crime Writers.
   Angela Lansbury and Vincent Price received Raven awards, named
for Poe's poem, for contributions to the world of mystery.
   Novelist Phyllis Whitney was named Grand Master of Mystery for
lifetime achievement.
   Edgars also went to ``Stakeout'' by Jim Kouf as best mystery
movie; ``Nutcracker'' by William Hanley as best TV movie; ``The
Musgrave Ritual,'' starring Sherlock Holmes, by Jeremy Paul, in the
PBS ``Mystery'' series, as best TV segment, and ``Bimbos of the
Death Sun'' by Sharyn McCrumb as best paperback original.
   ``Death Among Strangers,'' by Deidre S. Laiken, was chosen best
first mystery; ``CBS Murders'' by Richard Hammer best fact crime;
``Introduction to the Detective Story'' by Leroy Lad Panek best
critical study; ``Soft Monkey'' by Harlan Ellison best short story,
and ``Lucy Forever and Miss Rosetree, Shrinks'' by Susan Shreve
best juvenile mystery.
   Editor Ruth Cavin received the Ellery Queen Award for lifetime
achievement.
   Eric M. Heideman's ``Roger, Mr. Whilkie'' won the Robert Fish
Award for a short story.
</TEXT>
